" /><published>2020-04-26T00:00:00-05:00</published><updated>2020-04-26T00:00:00-05:00</updated><id>http://localhost:4000/2020/04/26/week-17</id><content type="html" xml:base="http://localhost:4000/2020/04/26/week-17.html">&lt;p&gt;I don't have much to say or show for this week, other than this website, which will be a form a motivation for me, by giving training the added meaning of &quot;creating content for the website&quot;).&lt;/p&gt;</content><author><name></name></author><category term="training logs" /><summary type="html">I don't have much to say or show for this week, other than this website, which will be a form a motivation for me, by giving training the added meaning of &quot;creating content for the website&quot;).</summary><media:thumbnail xmlns:media="http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/" url="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1538876777165-d225c410433d?ixlib=rb-1.2.1&amp;ixid=eyJhcHBfaWQiOjEyMDd9&amp;auto=format&amp;fit=crop&amp;w=1506&amp;q=80" /><media:content medium="image" url="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1538876777165-d225c410433d?ixlib=rb-1.2.1&amp;ixid=eyJhcHBfaWQiOjEyMDd9&amp;auto=format&amp;fit=crop&amp;w=1506&amp;q=80" xmlns:media="http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/" /></entry><entry><title type="html">Week 16: Fractured</title><link href="http://localhost:4000/2020/04/19/week-16.html" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="Week 16: Fractured
" /><published>2020-04-19T00:00:00-05:00</published><updated>2020-04-19T00:00:00-05:00</updated><id>http://localhost:4000/2020/04/19/week-16</id><content type="html" xml:base="http://localhost:4000/2020/04/19/week-16.html">&lt;p&gt;I put myself at increased risk of stress fracturing my foot: &lt;br /&gt;• wore new and different kinds of shoes &lt;br /&gt;• ran on new surfaces, uneven terrain &lt;br /&gt;• increased training load&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Seems these can take a few weeks to fully develop and become noticeable, so it’s likely the accumulation of these three things that did me in. I’ve done even higher volume than I’ve been doning, so that’s very unlikely to be the culprit. And my goal is to run on trail, so even if that is a cause, I wouldn’t have done anything differently. It’s the shoes I have control over, and that I probably should have controlled differently.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;For now, must avoid reproducing the pain. Reevaluate in 2-3 weeks. Brian says bones take six weeks to heal, so I’m thinking no training runs until then. Light jogs may be appropriate before then. We’ll see.&lt;/p&gt;</content><author><name></name></author><category term="training logs" /><summary type="html">I put myself at increased risk of stress fracturing my foot: • wore new and different kinds of shoes • ran on new surfaces, uneven terrain • increased training load</summary><media:thumbnail xmlns:media="http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/" url="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1573481214476-b644c8e2203d?ixlib=rb-1.2.1&amp;ixid=eyJhcHBfaWQiOjEyMDd9&amp;auto=format&amp;fit=crop&amp;w=2550&amp;q=80" /><media:content medium="image" url="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1573481214476-b644c8e2203d?ixlib=rb-1.2.1&amp;ixid=eyJhcHBfaWQiOjEyMDd9&amp;auto=format&amp;fit=crop&amp;w=2550&amp;q=80" xmlns:media="http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/" /></entry><entry><title type="html">Week 9: Day Brightoner</title><link href="http://localhost:4000/2020/03/01/week-09.html" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="Week 9: Day Brightoner
